## Problem 3: College Transfer Planning Advising

### The problem

Community college students who intend to transfer to a four-year institution face a complex and often opaque process. Articulation agreements between institutions specify which courses transfer and how they map to degree requirements, but these agreements vary by school, change over time, and are frequently buried in dense catalogs that students struggle to navigate. The consequences of poor transfer planning are: students take courses that do not count toward their intended degree, waste time and financial aid, and in some cases are forced to repeat coursework.

### Design considerations
• How would the system keep its articulation data current as institutions update their transfer policies?
• How should the system handle ambiguous or conflicting articulation rules across different target institutions?
• What safeguards would prevent students from relying on the system’s recommendations as a substitute for official academic advising?
• How do you design the system so that it is accessible and useful to first-generation college students who may be unfamiliar with transfer terminology?
• What happens when the system cannot find a clean transfer path — how does it communicate that honestly without discouraging the student?

